  <!-- ════════ CAUTIONS ════════ -->
  <section class="wd-section wd-cautions" id="cautions">
    <div class="wd-eyebrow">Read this before you act on any of it</div>
    <p class="wd-cautions-intro">This page is the trilogy&rsquo;s most timing-adjacent, so its guardrails are the strictest. It is a read on what history did at a position &mdash; never a signal that price will fall, and never a call to wait for a dip.</p>
    <div class="wd-caution-grid">
      <div class="wd-caution">
        <h3>Historical, not predictive</h3>
        <p>Every figure here is computed from what happened at this channel position since 2014. The Power Law is an empirical regularity, not a law of nature; past patterns cannot promise future prices. Use this to understand <em>risk at a position</em>, not to forecast the next move.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="wd-caution">
        <h3>&ldquo;Waiting&rdquo; is a position read, not a market call</h3>
        <p>Waiting here means holding out for a <em>lower channel position</em>, capped at two years &mdash; and the whole point is that the dip often never came. Nothing on this page tells you price will drop. When the waiting-paid rate is low, the clear reading is to <strong>deploy decisively</strong>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="wd-caution wd-caution-blindspot">
        <h3>Laddering is the response to risk, not a timing bet</h3>
        <p>High in the channel, the case for laddering or patience is a <strong>drawdown hedge</strong> &mdash; it trades some expected upside for staying power. It is not an attempt to call the top. If a drawdown would push you to capitulate, that hedge is worth more than the numbers show.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ════════ METHODOLOGY ════════ -->
  <div class="wd-method">
    <div class="wd-method-label">How these numbers are computed</div>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Channel position:</strong> the log-space location between the 0.42&times; floor and the 3&times; upper band, shown only as a &times;-trend multiple and its plain-language label &mdash; the same vocabulary as the rest of the trilogy.</li>
      <li><strong>Waiting (position-based):</strong> from an entry at position P, &ldquo;wait&rdquo; means hold out until channel position drops at least 0.15 below P, capped at two years. If no lower entry arrives in that window, the waiter deploys at the two-year price &mdash; waiting failed. Outcome is measured in <strong>Bitcoin acquired</strong> (1 / price), waiter versus deploy-now.</li>
      <li><strong>Waiting-paid rate:</strong> the share of historical entries near a position where waiting ended with more Bitcoin. <strong>Never-arrived:</strong> the share where no lower entry came within two years.</li>
      <li><strong>Drawdown:</strong> likelihood is the share of entries that fell at least 20% within two years; depth is the median worst drawdown. Its <strong>coins-equivalent</strong> is how much more Bitcoin the same dollars would buy at that trough.</li>
      <li><strong>Sample:</strong> post-2014 only (the pre-$15 curiosity era is excluded), and only entries with a full two-year forward record, so &ldquo;wait&rdquo; and &ldquo;drawdown within two years&rdquo; are never truncated by the edge of the data. Figures are recomputed live every page load.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

